<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a widespread and diverse genus encountered with relative frequency. Most species can be readily diagnosed by a dark brown notum with yellow shoulders and a sharply defined yellow medial stripe on the scutellum, and sometimes a stridulatory file anterolaterally in the male abdominal membrane (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 107–115" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figures 107 - 115. 107 Liriomyza sp., male, with arrow indicating stridulatory file 108 Liriomyza sp., female (S. A. Marshall - Cuba, Santiago) 109, 110 Liriomyza sativae (Blanchard), female 109 lateral 110 head, anterior 111, 112 Liriomyza trifolii (Burgess), female 111 head, anterior 112 lateral 113 Liriomyza asclepiadis Spencer, female (S. A. Marshall - Virginia, Craig County) 114 Liriomyza sp., female (S. A. Marshall - Ontario, Orangeville) 115 Liriomyza nigriscutellata Spencer, female (P. Bryant - California, Newport Beach)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1051.64603.figures107-115" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/572113" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">107</figureCitation>
). Much emphasis was previously placed on the presence of this stridulatory organ in the definition of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="von Tschirnhaus, M" journalOrPublisher="Beitraege zur Entomologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="551 - 579" refId="B279" refString="von Tschirnhaus, M, 1971. Unbekannte Stridulationsorgane bei Dipteren und ihre Bedeutung fϋr Taxonomie und Phylogenetik der Agromyziden. Beitraege zur Entomologie 21: 551 - 579" title="Unbekannte Stridulationsorgane bei Dipteren und ihre Bedeutung fϋr Taxonomie und Phylogenetik der Agromyziden." volume="21" year="1971">von Tschirnhaus 1971</bibRefCitation>
), but its presence is inconsistent across the genus, difficult to observe when present, and its real phylogenetic importance is yet to be fully appreciated. Definition of the genus is unfortunately somewhat nuanced at the moment. As discussed in 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 123" refId="B138" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2011. The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California. Zootaxa 2850: 1 - 123, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" title="The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" volume="2850" year="2011">Lonsdale (2011</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4234.1.1" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 156" refId="B142" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2017. The Liriomyza (Diptera: Schizophora: Agromyzidae) of Canada and Alaska. Zootaxa 4234 (1): 1 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4234.1.1" title="The Liriomyza (Diptera: Schizophora: Agromyzidae) of Canada and Alaska." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4234.1.1" volume="4234" year="2017">2017</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Zlobin, VV" journalOrPublisher="An International Journal of Dipterological Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="271 - 280" refId="B305" refString="Zlobin, VV, 1996. The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer. An International Journal of Dipterological Research 7 (4): 271 - 280" title="The genus Amauromyza Hendel (Diptera, Agromyzidae): a clarification of species of the subgenus Annimyzella Spencer." volume="7" year="1996">Zlobin (1996)</bibRefCitation>
, species of many other genera superficially resemble 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or are indistinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species externally, and a number of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
depart from the 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“typical”">&quot;typical&quot;</normalizedToken>
colour form described above. These species are either predominantly dark on the thorax and sometimes the head, such as those species previously treated as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spencer" authorityYear="1981" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Galiomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Galiomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Galiomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or they have reduced chaetotaxy and venation and/or pale grey pruinosity on the thorax, resembling 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Steyskal" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Haplopeodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Haplopeodes" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Haplopeodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, or they are predominantly yellow, as in some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Phytoliriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phytoliriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phytoliriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The genus is presently defined solely by a male genitalic character that is consistently present: an ejaculatory duct that is both swollen and pigmented apically. A single genitalic character is clearly not ideal in the definition of a genus, and it is hoped that ongoing phylogenetic work can provide additional characters by clarifying 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
's position with respect to related groups, ideally characters that are visible externally in both sexes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1894" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains many of the most pestiferous species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="? arthropoda" rank="family">Agromyzidae</taxonomicName>
, the Nearctic species of which were discussed by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 123" refId="B138" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2011. The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California. Zootaxa 2850: 1 - 123, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" title="The Liriomyza (Agromyzidae: Schizophora: Diptera) of California." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.2850.1.1" volume="2850" year="2011">Lonsdale (2011)</bibRefCitation>
, who provided a list of host genera. Of these pests, only 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. brassicae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="brassicae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. brassicae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Riley), 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. sativae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sativae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. sativae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Blanchard and 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. trifolii" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trifolii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. trifolii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Burgess) occur in the eastern United States.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
In addition to the species redescribed below, Spencer and Steyskal (1986) listed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hering" authorityYear="1955" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Liriomyza" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Liriomyza endiviae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="endiviae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liriomyza endiviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hering as occurring in Maryland and Washington State. The Maryland record is represented only by observations of empty leaf mines in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Asteraceae" genus="Lactuca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Lactuca" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Lactuca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and since species identity cannot be verified and may have been in error, 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. endiviae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="endiviae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. endiviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here not considered to occur in the eastern United States. All other Nearctic specimens previously identified as 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. endiviae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="endiviae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. endiviae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were examined by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4234.1.1" author="Lonsdale, O" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 156" refId="B142" refString="Lonsdale, O, 2017. The Liriomyza (Diptera: Schizophora: Agromyzidae) of Canada and Alaska. Zootaxa 4234 (1): 1 - 156, DOI: https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4234.1.1" title="The Liriomyza (Diptera: Schizophora: Agromyzidae) of Canada and Alaska." url="https://doi.org/10.11646/zootaxa.4234.1.1" volume="4234" year="2017">Lonsdale (2017)</bibRefCitation>
and have been determined to belong to another species, most likely 
<taxonomicName family="Hydrangeaceae" genus="L." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="L. taraxaci" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="taraxaci">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">L. taraxaci</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
